node.text:
The photographs of LIFE photographer Bob Gomel provide an intimate look at some of the 20th century's greatest figures: Muhammad Ali, JFK, the Beatles, Malcolm X, and more.

“I had no idea the ‘60s would be so iconic,” Gomel, 88, said recently in a phone interview. “It seemed quite ordinary at the time, but looking back on it now, I realize how fortunate I was.”

To learn more about these photos—and the great photographer himself—tap the link in bio.

node.text:
Rest in peace to the late, great Charlie Watts. The Rolling Stones drummer passed away yesterday at age 80.

LIFE's Kostya Kennedy wrote of the band's incredible sound, "Charlie Watts drove the action, cool and swinging on his simple kit..."

For more on one of the most iconic bands in the world, tap the link in bio.

(📷DMI, 1993 / LIFE Picture Collection)

#lifemagazine #rollingstones #charliewatts #drummersofinstagram #charliewattsforever

node.text:
Professor Hubert Alyea teaches chemistry in his Princeton classroom, 1953.

“Grimacing with fiendish delight,” LIFE wrote of Alyea’s teaching, “he sets off explosions, shoots water pistols and sprays his audience with carbon dioxide...His fiery performances destroy three suits of clothing a year."

For more on the chemistry teacher you wish you had (his nickname was "Dr. Boom" and he was the inspiration for a hit film!), tap the link in bio.

(📷Yale Joel / LIFE Picture Collection)

#stemeducation #lifemagazine #yalejoel #1950sfashion #princeton #chemistrylab

node.text:
The legendary actor, dancer, inventor, and activist Julie Newmar is 88 today.

In 1960, LIFE's editors wrote, "when people talk about girls who are likely to be regarded as national treasures one day, the name of [this] long-legged, astonishingly beautiful girl is sure to come up. She is Julie Newmar..."

To learn more about this national treasure (and iconic Catwoman!), tap the link in bio.

(📷Ralph Morse, 1958/LIFE Picture Collection)

#julienewmar #lifemagazine #ralphmorse #1950sfashion

In the summer of 1969, LIFE traveled around Manhattan to define the "New York Look." The Look, they found, was "bright, bold, unpredictable—and above all young...a daily celebration of the self."

To see the original article and outtakes from the story, tap the link in bio.

(📷Vernon Merritt/LIFE Picture Collection)

node.text:
Meet LIFE staff photographer—and Olympic rower—Co Rentmeester. 

Born in Amsterdam in 1936, Rentmeester has lived a fascinating life, creating some of the most renowned photographs of the past century: Watts in 1965, the Vietnam War (where he was shot on assignment), the Munich massacre, even the Michael Jordan photo that may have served as the basis for the Nike logo. "I was burning with energy," Rentmeester said of his career.

To see his photographs and to learn more about this living legend, tap the link in bio.

(📷Co Rentmeester / LIFE Picture Collection, 1968)

#lifemagazine #corentmeester #wildLIFEwednesday #famousphotographers #worldpressphotowinner

node.text:
The Louvre opened to the public on August 10, 1793. LIFE's photographers were frequent visitors throughout the 20th century, including Dmitri Kessel, who caught this jaunty conservator restoring Théodore Géricault's Raft of the Medusa. 

For another LIFE visit to the Louvre, tap the link in bio.

(📷Dmitri Kessel, 1950 / LIFE Picture Collection)
